g.', 9623, 0), (403231, 'Brotherhood is the very price and condition of man''s survival.', 51826, 0), (403232, 'One thing everybody in the world wants and needs is friendliness.', 63859, 0), (403233, 'A man cannot be said to succeed in this life who does not satisfy one friend.', 1049, 0), (403234, 'We take care of our health  we lay up money  we make our roof tight and our clothing sufficient  but who provides wisely that he shall not be wanting in the best property of all-friends.', 760, 0), (403235, 'There is no physician like a true friend.', 33, 0), (403236, 'There is nothing meritorious but virtue and friendship.', 3348, 0), (403237, 'The bird  a nest  the spider  a web  man  friendship.', 221, 0), (403238, 'True happiness ... arises  in the first place  from the enjoyment of one''s self  and in the next from the friendship and conversation of a few select companions.', 2868, 0), (403239, 'It was such a joy to see thee. I wish I could tell how much thee is to my life. I always turn to thee as a sort of rest.', 63860, 0), (403240, 'Today a man discovered gold and fame  Another flew the stormy seas  Another set an unarmed world aflame  One found the germ of a disease. But what high fates my path attend: For I-today-I found a friend.', 63855, 0), (403241, 'Good friends  good books and a sleepy conscience: this is the ideal life.', 286, 0), (403242, 'Man is a knot  a web  a mesh into which relationships are tied. Only those relationships matter.', 69, 0), (403243, 'Friendship is the only cement that will ever hold the world together.', 1970, 0), (403244, 'Friends are an aid to the young  to guard them from error  to the elderly  to attend to their wants and to supplement their failing power of action  to those in the prime of life  to assist them to noble deeds.', 1116, 0), (403245, 'Friendship is the allay of our sorrows  the ease of our passions  the discharge of our oppression  the sanctuary of our calamities  the counselor of our doubts  the clarity of our minds  the emission of our thoughts  the exercise and improvement of what we dedicate.', 3943, 0), (403246, 'Of all the things which wisdom provides to make life entirely happy  much the greatest is the possession of friendship.', 1839, 0), (403247, 'There''s nothing worth the wear of winning but laughter  and the love of friends.', 4439, 0), (403248, 'Each friend represents a world in us  a world possibly not born until they arrive  and it is only by this meeting that a new world is born.', 23, 0), (403249, 'The feeling of friendship is like that of being comfortably filled with roast beef  love  like being enlivened with champagne.', 2087, 0), (403250, 'One is taught by experience to put a premium on those few people who can appreciate you for what you are.', 15819, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (403251, 'Oh Dear! How unfortunate I am not to have anyone to weep with!', 63849, 0), (403252, 'The worst solitude is to be destitute of sincere friendship.', 1035, 0), (403253, 'If you want an accounting of your worth  count your friends.', 63055, 0), (403254, 'A man with few friends is only half-developed  there are whole sides of his nature which are locked up and have never been expressed. He cannot unlock them himself  he cannot even discover them  friends alone can stimulate him and open him.', 4976, 0), (403255, 'Tis the human touch in the world that counts-the touch of your hand and mine-Which means far more to the sinking heart than shelter or bread or wine For shelter is gone when the night is o''er  and bread lasts only a day But the touch of the hand and the sound of the voice Live on in the soul always.', 63861, 0), (403256, 'Good company and good discourse are the very sinews of virtue.', 62724, 0), (403257, 'Friends are the sunshine of life.', 21494, 0), (403258, 'My friends have made the story of my life. In a thousand ways they have turned my limitations into beautiful privileges  and enabled me to walk serene and happy in the shadow cast by my deprivation.', 701, 0), (403259, 'The support of one''s personality is friends. A part of one''s self and a real foundation and existence.', 62244, 0), (403260, 'No greater burden can be born by an individual than to know none who cares or understands.', 63862, 0), (403261, 'My life seems to have become suddenly hollow  and I do not know what is hanging over me. I cannot even put the shadow that has fallen on me into words. At least into written words. I would give a great deal for a friend''s voice.', 63863, 0), (403262, 'A true friend is the best possession.', 33, 0), (403263, 'It is not so much our friends'' help that helps us  as the confidence of their help.', 1839, 0), (403264, 'Friends Make Life Bearable But I have certainty enough  For I am sure of you.', 62313, 0), (403265, 'Best friend  my well-spring in the wilderness!', 215, 0), (403266, 'Plant a seed of friendship  reap a bouquet of happiness.', 63864, 0), (403267, 'Our happiness in this world depends on the affections we are able to inspire.', 63865, 0), (403268, 'Some people go to priests  others to poetry  I to my friends.', 113, 0), (403269, 'The family. We are a strange little band of characters trudging through life sharing diseases and toothpaste  coveting one another''s desserts  hiding shampoo  locking each other out of our rooms  inflicting pain and kissing to heal it in the same instant  loving  laughing  defending  and trying to figure out the common thread that bound us all together.', 152, 0), (403270, 'You hear a lot of dialogue on the death of the American family. Families aren''t dying. They''re merging into big conglomerates.', 152, 0), (403271, 'If ever two were one  then surely we. If ever man were loved by wife  then thee.', 1211, 0), (403272, 'Friends are the family we choose for ourselves.', 49145, 0), (403273, 'I think togetherness is a very important ingredient to family life. It''s a cliche and we use it too much but I think for a husband and wife  the way to stay close is to do things together and share.', 11962, 0), (403274, 'Jimmy and I were always partners.', 19480, 0), (403275, 'He [Winston Churchill] has a future and I have a past  so we should be all right.', 62234, 0), (403276, 'Parents are friends that life gives us  friends are parents that the heart chooses.', 63039, 0), (403277, '[My father] was generous with his affection  given to great  awkward  engulfing hugs  and I can remember so clearly the smell of his hugs  all starched shirt  tobacco  Old Spice  and Cutty Sark. Sometimes I think I''ve never been properly hugged since.', 10161, 0), (403278, 'Both within the family and without  our sisters hold up our mirrors: our images of who we are and of who we can dare to become.', 63866, 0), (403279, 'Sisters define their rivalry in terms of competition for the gold cup of parental love. It is never perceived as a cup which runneth over  rather a finite vessel from which the more one sister drinks  the less is left over for the others.', 63866, 0), (403280, 'The desire to be and have a sister is a primitive and profound one that may have everything or nothing to do with the family a woman is born to. It is a desire to know and be known by someone who shares blood and body  history and dreams.', 63866, 0), (403281, 'Where there is lasting love  there is a family.', 63867, 0), (403282, 'Is solace anywhere more comforting than in the arms of sisters?', 753, 0), (403283, 'Call it a clan  call it a network  call it a tribe  call it a family: Whatever you call it  whoever you are  you need one.', 63158, 0), (403284, 'Old as she was  she still missed her daddy sometimes.', 185, 0), (403285, '[Families] are made to make you forget yourself occasionally  so that the beautiful balance of life is not destroyed.', 23, 0), (403286, 'The family unit plays a critical role in our society and in the training of the generation to come.', 10500, 0), (403287, 'Families will not be broken. Curse and expel them  send their children wandering  drown them in floods and fires  and old women will make songs of all these sorrows and sit in the porches and sing them on mild evenings.', 1383, 0), (403288, 'The family is the building block for whatever solidarity there is in society.', 63868, 0), (403289, 'Who ran to help me when I fell And would some pretty story tell Or kiss the place to make it well? My mother.', 6165, 0), (403290, 'All love that has not friendship for its base  Is like a mansion built upon the sand.', 541, 0), (403291, 'One can find traces of every life in each life.', 5094, 0), (403292, 'Friendship is an art  and very few persons are born with a natural gift for it.', 4775, 0), (403293, 'The art of friendship has been little cultivated in our society.', 63869, 0), (403294, 'We flatter those we scarcely know  We please the fleeting guest  And deal full many a thoughtless blow To those who love us best.', 541, 0), (403295, 'Good friendships are fragile things and require as much care as any other fragile and precious thing.', 4976, 0), (403296, 'Remember that you are all people and that all people are you.', 7613, 0), (403297, 'Human beings are born into this little span of life of which the best thing is its friendships and intimacies ... and yet they leave their friendships and intimacies with no cultivation  to grow as they will by the roadside  expecting them to "keep" by force of mere inertia.', 1782, 0), (403298, 'The only way to have a friend is to be one.', 760, 0), (403299, 'Friendships  like marriages  are dependent on avoiding the unforgivable.', 8000, 0), (403300, 'Beware of the danger signals that flag problems: silence  secretiveness  or sudden outburst.', 46635, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (403301, 'To accept a favor from a friend is to confer one.', 63642, 0), (403302, 'There is a magnet in your heart that will attract true friends. That magnet is unselfishness  thinking of others first... when you learn to live for others  they will live for you.', 2055, 0), (403303, 'Blessed are they who have the gift of making friends  for it is one of God''s best gifts. It involves many things  but above all  the power of getting out of one''s self  and appreciating whatever is noble and loving in another.', 33868, 0), (403304, 'Don''t ask of your friends what you yourself can do.', 15552, 0), (403305, 'Half the secret of getting along with people is consideration of their values  the other half is tolerance in one''s own views.', 63870, 0), (403306, 'A true friend unbosoms freely  advises justly  assists readily  adventures boldly  takes all patiently  defends courageously  and continues a friend unchangeably.', 3256, 0), (403307, 'Confidence is the foundation of friendship. If we give it  we will receive it.', 63871, 0), (403308, 'There is a definite process by which one made people into friends  and it involved talking to them and listening to them for hours at a time.', 7216, 0), (403309, 'Actions  not words  are the true criterion of the attachment of friends.', 3161, 0), (403310, 'One who knows how to show and to accept kindness will be a friend better than any possession.', 139, 0), (403311, 'Any man will usually get from other men what he is expecting from them. If he is looking for friendship  he will likely receive it. If his attitude is that of indifference  it will beget indifference. And if a man is looking for a fight  he will in all likelihood be accommodated in that.', 63872, 0), (403312, 'There is nothing we like to see so much as the gleam of pleasure in a person''s eye when he feels that we have sympathized with him  understood him  interested ourself in his welfare. At these moments something fine and spiritual passes between two friends. These moments are the moments worth living.', 2692, 0), (403313, 'He does good to himself who does good to his friend.', 1966, 0), (403314, 'A sense of duty is useful in work  but offensive in personal relations. People wish to be liked  not endured with patient resignation.', 95, 0), (403315, 'When a friend is in trouble  don''t annoy him by asking if there is anything you can do. Think up something appropriate and do it.', 20175, 0), (403316, 'Loyalty is what we seek in friendship.', 20928, 0), (403317, 'True friendship comes when silence between two people is comfortable.', 63667, 0), (403318, 'If two friends ask you to judge a dispute  don''t accept  because you will lose one friend  on the other hand  if two strangers come with the same request  accept  because you will gain one friend.', 63060, 0), (403319, 'Perhaps the most delightful friendships are those in which there is much agreement  much disputation  and yet more personal liking.', 215, 0), (403320, 'There can be no friendship when there is no freedom. Friendship loves the free air  and will not be fenced up in straight and narrow enclosures.', 3256, 0), (403321, 'You will find yourself refreshed by the presence of cheerful people. Why not make earnest effort to confer that pleasure on others?...Half the battle is gained if you never allow yourself to say anything gloomy.', 59119, 0), (403322, 'Wear a smile and have friends  wear a scowl and have wrinkles.', 215, 0), (403323, 'Lead the life that will make you kindly and friendly to everyone about you  and you will be surprised what a happy life you will live.', 63087, 0), (403324, 'Those who cannot give friendship will rarely receive it  and never hold it.', 29049, 0), (403325, 'It is not the services we render them  but the services they render us  that attaches people to us.', 63873, 0), (403326, 'We cherish our friends not for their ability to amuse us  but for ours to amuse them.', 399, 0), (403327, 'It is foolish to make experiments upon the constancy of a friend  as upon the chastity of a wife.', 2087, 0), (403328, 'Give and take makes good friends.', 60338, 0), (403329, 'A quarrel between friends  when made up  adds a new tie to friendship  as ... the callosity formed ''round a broken bone makes it stronger than before.', 63291, 0), (403330, 'No real friendship is ever made without an initial clashing which discloses the metal of each to each.', 10420, 0), (403331, 'Nothing wounds a friend like a want of confidence.', 63874, 0), (403332, 'The first thing to learn in intercourse with others is non-interference with their own peculiar ways of being happy  provided those ways do not assume to interfere with ours.', 1782, 0), (403333, 'No man can have society upon his own terms. If he seeks it  he must serve it too.', 760, 0), (403334, 'We cannot tell the precise moment when friendship is formed. As in filling a vessel drop by drop  there is at last a drop which makes it run over. So in a series of kindnesses there is  at last  one which makes the heart run over.', 23243, 0), (403335, 'Friendship is a plant which must be often watered.', 33, 0), (403336, 'A friend should bear his friend''s infirmities.', 13, 0), (403337, 'No man is much pleased with a companion who does not increase  in some respect  his fondness of himself.', 2087, 0), (403338, 'You win the victory when you yield to friends.', 139, 0), (403339, 'The condition which high friendship demands is the ability to do without it.', 760, 0), (403340, 'Women can form a friendship with a man very well  but to preserve it  a slight physical antipathy most probably helps.', 11, 0), (403341, 'Love your friends as if they would some day hate you.', 63875, 0), (403342, 'Friendship is a strong and habitual inclination in two persons to promote the good and happiness of one another.', 15466, 0), (403343, 'Friendship is the pleasing game of interchanging praise.', 24754, 0), (403344, 'The hardest of all is learning to be a well of affection  and not a fountain  to show them that we love them  not when we feel like it  but when they do.', 63876, 0), (403345, 'If you want to be listened to  you should put in time listening.', 8930, 0), (403346, '"Stay" is a charming word in a friend''s vocabulary.', 296, 0), (403347, 'The only service a friend can really render is to keep up your courage by holding up to you a mirror in which you can see a noble image of yourself.', 266, 0), (403348, 'The way to make a true friend is to be one. Friendship implies loyalty  esteem  cordiality  sympathy  affection  readiness to aid  to help  to stick  to fight for  if need be. ... Radiate friendship and it will return sevenfold.', 14130, 0), (403349, 'The most called-upon prerequisite of a friend is an accessible ear.', 74, 0), (403350, 'A loyal friend laughs at your jokes when they''re not so good  and sympathizes with your problems when they''re not so bad.', 63877, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (403351, 'Politeness is an inexpensive way of making friends.', 5249, 0), (403352, 'The secret of success in society is a certain heartiness and sympathy.', 760, 0), (403353, 'Sometimes we owe a friend to the lucky circumstance that we give him no cause for envy.', 11, 0), (403354, 'Friendship requires great communication.', 63291, 0), (403355, 'Friendship requires more time than poor busy men can usually command.', 760, 0), (403356, 'We should behave to our friends as we would wish our friends to behave to us.', 1116, 0), (403357, 'You can make more friends in two months by becoming more interested in other people than you can in two years by trying to get people interested in you.', 33, 0), (403358, 'We secure our friends not by accepting favors but by doing them.', 2096, 0), (403359, 'Friendship multiplies the good of life and divides the evil. Tis the sole remedy against misfortune  the very ventilation of the soul.', 1255, 0), (403360, 'It is easier to visit friends than to live with them.', 7652, 0), (403361, 'The loneliness you get by the sea is personal and alive. It doesn''t subdue you and make you feel abject. It''s stimulating loneliness.', 1407, 0), (403362, 'The chain of friendship  however bright  does not stand the attrition of constant close contact.', 50656, 0), (403363, 'Fond as we are of our loved ones  there comes at times during their absence an unexplained peace.', 63878, 0), (403364, 'Friendship increases in visiting friends  but not in visiting them too often.', 33, 0), (403365, 'Go oft to the house of thy friend  for weeds choke the unused path.', 760, 0), (403366, 'I am quite sure that no friendship yields its true pleasure and nobility of nature without frequent communication  sympathy and service.', 2015, 0), (403367, 'I am learning to live close to the lives of my friends without ever seeing them. No miles of any measurement can separate your soul from mine.', 1402, 0), (403368, '